entry.title: [EditContext] Ensure that ExecutionContext of the associated element is used
entry.content:
Currently if an author tries to associate an EditContext with an

Element in a document that's different from the document where it was

constructed, the EditContext will make the associated element editable

but not capture text input. The reason is that in

`EditContext::Focus()`,

the call to do `GetInputMethodController().SetActiveEditContext(this)`

is getting the InputMethodController for the ExecutionContext that

the EditContext was constructed with, not the InputMethodController

for the document the EditContext is now associated with. So to the

InputMethodController that ends up receiving the text input, it

looks like there is no active EditContext.



Fix this by updating the EditContext's ExecutionContext whenever an

associated element is set.



An alternative considered was to have EditContext no longer store

the ExecutionContext directly at all and instead always get it from

the associated element. However there are some cases where this is

problematic. For example when DispatchTextFormatEvent is called

immediately before DispatchCompositionEndEvent, the EditContext

could be detached from its element in the textformatupdate

handler, which would then cause problems in

DispatchCompositionEndEvent since it uses the ExecutionContext

via the DomWindow() call.

entry.title: [Site search policy] Support for site search in TemplateURL
entry.content:
This CL makes the following changes to `TemplateURL` for the new

SiteSearchSettings Enterprise policy:

- Add a new field `featured_by_policy` to indicate when a SE should

be featured in the Omnibox

- Changes the type of field `created_by_policy` from a boolean to

an enum to represent which policy introduced the SE:

- 0 = no policy

- 1 = Default Search Provider policy

- 2 = Site Search policy



This is the downstream effect in the keywords DB table:

- Add a new column corresponding to `featured_by_policy`

- Change the code that reads and writes entries to the table to

convert to/from the enum instead of a boolean



There is no need to change the table schema for the `created_by_policy`

field, because the corresponding column is already an integer with

the same representation as above (0: no policy, 1: DSP policy).



Screenshots: b/307544344#comment5



We were originally planning to only add `featured_by_policy` to `TemplateURL`, but unfortunately that doesn't allow us to

differentiate from the default search provider set by policy:



- Today, there are two booleans to represent policy state:

`created_by_policy` (DSP policy) and `enforced_by_policy` (whether

the policy is required or recommended)

- Those two booleans represent 3 valid states: no policy, policy is

mandatory, policy is recommended

- The site search policy is mandatory only in the initial version, but

we may eventually support the recommended state -> that will require

us to support more states than currently possible



Please refer to crrev.com/c/5017736 for a discussion on alternatives.



Bug: b/309457587, b/307544344

entry.title: Add an enabled-by-default flag for iframe support of adAuctionHeaders.
entry.content:
The iframe support for adAuctionHeaders is still guarded by the

`kFledgeNegativeTargeting` flag, and this remains the flag that controls

the enablement of the `adAuctionHeaders` attribute on the iframe element.

However, we add a separate `kEnableIFrameAdAuctionHeaders` flag that can

be disabled to remove iframe navigation handling of the ad auction

response headers. When `kEnableIFrameAdAuctionHeaders` is disabled, the `Ad-Auction-Signals` and `Ad-Auction-Additional-Bid` response headers are still cleared for iframes that specify the `adAuctionHeaders` attribute, but this has no user-visible impact because iframe navigation offers no programmatic access to the response headers.

entry.title: Consistently clear sync metadata on SyncMode changes
entry.content:
Sync metadata should usually be cleared when Sync is stopped, and any

left-behind metadata should eventually get cleaned up - and after

crbug.com/897628, that was generally the case. But there was one edge

case that wasn't handled yet: When the Sync machinery missed a switch

between "full Sync" (aka Sync-the-feature) and transport mode, the

metadata of the "other" (now-inactive) mode would be left behind and

not cleaned up.

This CL fixes this by doing two things:

* Adding ClearMetadataWhileStopped() calls (on both delegates i.e.

processors) in ModelLoadManager::LoadModels(), after the correct

delegate was started.

* Changing the semantics of ClearMetadataWhileStopped() so that it's

a no-op if the type in question is not actually stopped.

Together, this means the metadata of the "wrong" mode gets cleared,

without affecting the metadata of the "correct" mode.

entry.title: Add infrastructure to maintain the type used to fill an AutofilledField
entry.content:
Currently, Autofill only uses the classified type of a field in order to

fill it. In the future, this might change and we might sometimes

fallback to other types in case the classified type doesn't lead to a

successful filling.



In that case, `AutofillField::overall_type_` stops representing

accurately the filling state of the field, which might be needed by

other components.



This CL:

- Adds an `autofilled_type_` optional data member to AutofillField

tracking the type used to fill that field by Autofill.

- Adds logic to retrieve this information from the cache since this

information does not come from the renderer and hence newly built

AutofillFields cannot assign it.

- Adds logic to maintain history of that data member so that Undo

operations keeps this information consistent with the other states of

the field.

- Adds minimal logic to set this type whenever a field is autofilled.



Logic that will compute fallback types is out of scope of this CL.



This CL is a no-op.

entry.title: Revert^2 "Use the built-in Cronet telemetry stack"
entry.content:
This reverts commit e0d51530c73028dbdb7799a901adf00f1448665c.



Reason for revert: re-landing following https://crrev.com/c/5040785



Original change's description:

> Revert "Use the built-in Cronet telemetry stack"

>

> This reverts commit 3edea021bad8fdafebc2d11fb9bdc0266ce6d0e3.

>

> Reason for revert: Needed for another revert: https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/5041483

>

> Bug: https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=1503204

>

> Original change's description:

> > Use the built-in Cronet telemetry stack

> >

> > Before this CL, Cronet expected to be shipped with a CronetLoggerImpl

> > class that lives outside of Chromium:

> >

> > - In the case of AOSP Cronet, that class would be built from AOSP along

> > with the rest of Cronet;

> > - In the case of Cronet embedded in Google 1P apps and Google Play

> > Services it would be built from an internal Google repo and the

> > resulting compiled class would be injected into the Cronet JAR at APK

> > build time;

> > - In any other cases (e.g. Maven) the class would not be present at

> > all.

> >

> > The above setup is extremely contrived and requires maintaining an

> > API/ABI boundary across 3 different repos, making this code very painful

> > to maintain. We have to juggle between all these repos every time we

> > make any changes to telemetry atom schemas, which is something we expect

> > to do somewhat regularly in the future. This is not sustainable.

> >

> > This CL simplifies the whole setup by making Cronet use the telemetry

> > code that was recently imported from AOSP into Chromium for this

> > purpose. From this point on, the entire telemetry logic lives in

> > Chromium and can be maintained just like the rest of Cronet code in the

> > normal way.

> >

> > The AOSP and internal code that attempts to inject a CronetLoggerImpl

> > class will have no effect after this CL - that code will become dead and

> > we should clean it up as soon as this commit makes it to these repos.

> >

> > The only downside of this change is that the atom definition still lives

> > elsewhere - the source of truth for that is in an internal Google

> > repo since the code that consumes the telemetry data is Google-internal.

> > The CronetStatsLog code is supposed to be autogenerated at build time

> > from the atom definition, but the relevant code generator only exists in

> > AOSP (under the name "stats-log-api-gen") and in the internal repo - it

> > does not exist in Chromium. So, for now, we'll have to run the code

> > generator manually and then manually copy its output over to Chromium,

> > every time we change atom definitions. This is not ideal, but that's a

> > small price to pay for the massive simplification that this CL brings.

> > Eventually we should solve this by having the atom proto definition in

> > Chromium (ideally autosynced from the internal repo) and then

> > autogenerate the logging code from it at build time in Chromium.

> >

entry.title: [a11y] Move some of serialization pipeline from RAI to cache.
entry.content:
This CL aims to start moving some of the code path starting from HandleAXEvent to ScheduleImmediateAXUpdate over to cache side. The old code is still left in RAI for legacy support.



The aim is to eventually delete the code from RAI side, and then RAI would only be called from ProcessDeferredAccessibilityEvents to AXReadyCallback.



----------------------------

Details (only explaining post-lifecyle mode):

Before this CL, a11y events (kind of) go like this: AXObjectCacheImpl::PostPlatformNotification -> RenderAccessibilityImpl::HandleAXEvent which also calls AXObjectCacheImpl::AddPendingEvent --> RenderAccessibilityImpl::ScheduleImmediateAXUpdate -> AXObjectCacheImpl::ScheduleAXUpdate --> AXObjectCacheImpl::ProcessDeferredAccessibilityEvents -> RenderAccessibilityImpl::AXReadyCallback



Note that -> doesn't mean direct calls. Some calls in the middle may have been skipped. The CL prevents these excessively unnecessary calls in between RAI (RenderAccessibilityImpl) and AXObjectCacheImpl. The calls now go like this (again kinda): AXObjectCacheImpl::PostPlatformNotification -> AXObjectCacheImpl::AddEventToSerializationQueue -> AXObjectCacheImpl::ScheduleImmediateSerialization -> AXObjectCacheImpl::ScheduleAXUpdate -> AXObjectCacheImpl::ProcessDeferredAccessibilityEvents -> RenderAccessibilityImpl::AXReadyCallback



Notice how RAI is only called at the very end. Of course, to make this possible many of the side logic had to be moved too like the delaying code that used to be AXReadyCallback is now at AXObjectCacheImpl::ProcessDeferredAccessibilityEvents.



This image describes the above: https://i.imgur.com/U3tODTX.png

What the CL achieves is moving the code in the blue square over to the left-hand side, thus making the code stay in AXObjectCache longer and only move to RAI at RenderAccessibilityImpl::AXReadyCallback. The serialization delay is moved to ProcessDeferredAccessibilityEvents.



----------------------------

Legacy scheduling mode (as opposed to post-lifecycle serialization) still uses the old code which goes back and forth between RAI and AXObjectCache. The reason they were not moved as well is that legacy mode will get removed eventually anyway. When legacy mode is removed, we can safely remove the old code from RAI.



----------------------------

Also, with the cleaner code, it'll be feasible to change the scheduling logic further to limit some events like scrolling. Scrolling improvements discussed here https://docs.google.com/document/d/1fBK1BBrG8souqZpyv7q_3kxCYF1IYoXNPXmoVL7X8Gk/edit#heading=h.uo8ebdp7cxl



----------------------------

However, the test template cannot distinguish between Rust and non-Rust

dependencies, so building a tests containing Rust sources will actually

include command-line arguments to include the whole archive for

dependencies that aren't Rust at all, and do not even have a .rlib file.



In addition:

- the Windows linker (lld-link in Chrome) errors out if a non-existent

path is used with '/WHOLEARCHIVE:'

- this logic does not encapsulate transitive dependencies (e.g. if a

unit test depends on a GN group that contains Rust static libraries

with tests)



Rather than the test templates trying to fix up linking ex-post-facto,

this CL propagates required linking directives upwards through the build

graph by using all_dependent_configs. To avoid force including *all*

testonly static libs, this CL also re-introduces the use of the

`is_gtest_unittests` GN variable for `rust_static_library`. Only targets

that specify `is_gtest_unittests = true` will propagate a linker config

to include the whole archive of the .rlib.



Finally, to avoid issues with #[gtest(...)] static initializers being

silently dropped, the proc macro now errors out if a Rust target tries

to use the proc macro without setting `is_gtest_unittests = true` in its

GN target.
